#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:1
msgid "Compiler Optimizations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:3
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide already benefits from optimizations in rustc and LLVM. The `mir-"
"transforms` crate is where cuda-oxide adds its own passes while a program is "
"still represented as `dialect-mir`. Loop unrolling is the first cuda-oxide-"
"owned optimization pass in this layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:8
msgid ""
"This page starts with the user-facing idea, then follows one loop through "
"the compiler. You do not need compiler experience to read it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:13
msgid "What is a MIR transform?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:15
msgid ""
"After rustc lowers Rust source to MIR, cuda-oxide imports it into `dialect-"
"mir`, where typed operations and control-flow branches are explicit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:18
msgid "There are three related jobs in this part of the compiler:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "Job"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "What it does"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "**Analysis**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "Reads the IR and records facts, such as which blocks form a loop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "**Transform**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "Rewrites the IR without changing what the program computes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "**Lowering**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:0
msgid "Converts the program from one IR dialect into a lower-level dialect"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:26
msgid ""
"Loop analysis can identify a loop's counter, step, and bound. The unroll "
"transform uses those facts to rewrite the loop so that each trip performs "
"several original iterations. Lowering later converts the result to LLVM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:31
msgid ""
"In this chapter, **MIR transforms** means transforms over cuda-oxide's "
"imported `dialect-mir`. They do not modify rustc's internal MIR directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:37
msgid "Where transforms run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:39
msgid ""
"The optimization layer sits in the middle of the device compilation pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:41
msgid ""
"Rust source\n"
"    → rustc MIR\n"
"    → mir-importer\n"
"    → dialect-mir\n"
"    → mem2reg\n"
"    → mir-transforms       ← cuda-oxide optimizations\n"
"    → mir-lower\n"
"    → LLVM dialect\n"
"    → LLVM IR\n"
"    → PTX\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:54
msgid ""
"The [MIR importer](mir-importer.md) initially represents local variables "
"with loads and stores. `mem2reg` promotes eligible locals to **SSA values**, "
"where each value has one definition and block arguments carry values between "
"blocks. That makes loop counters and their updates explicit enough for an "
"optimization pass to reason about."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:60
msgid ""
"Transforms run here because `dialect-mir` retains Rust-level types and "
"operations, making targeted cuda-oxide rewrites easier to express. The "
"[lowering pipeline](lowering-pipeline.md) then converts the optimized result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:64
msgid ""
"Full variable-debug builds skip `mem2reg` and loop unrolling. Keeping source "
"variables in stable memory locations gives cuda-gdb a better debugging "
"experience."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:70
msgid "The first pass: loop unrolling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:72
msgid ""
"A loop normally tests its condition and branches back after every iteration. "
"**Unrolling** copies the body so that one trip through the new loop performs "
"several iterations' work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:76
msgid "Consider this small counted loop inside a kernel or device function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:78
msgid ""
"let mut i = 0u32;\n"
"#[unroll]\n"
"while i < 4 {\n"
"    work(i);\n"
"    i += 1;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:87
msgid "Conceptually, full unrolling turns it into:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:89
msgid ""
"work(0);\n"
"work(1);\n"
"work(2);\n"
"work(3);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:96
msgid ""
"The condition and branch back to the loop header disappear. More "
"importantly, each copy now has a constant value for `i`, exposing further "
"simplifications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:99
msgid ""
"The tradeoff is larger generated code. A larger body may also need more "
"registers, so unrolling is a request to the compiler, not a promise of "
"better performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:105
msgid "Full and partial unrolling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:107
msgid "cuda-oxide provides two forms:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "Annotation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "Use it when"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "What the pass produces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "`#[unroll]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "The trip count is known at compile time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "One body copy per iteration; the loop disappears"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "`#[unroll(N)]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "The trip count may be known only at runtime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:30
msgid "`N` copies in a main loop, plus a remainder loop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:114
msgid "Full unrolling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:116
msgid "Bare `#[unroll]` needs a compile-time-known trip count:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:118
msgid ""
"let mut i = 0u32;\n"
"#[unroll]\n"
"while i < 8 {\n"
"    sum += i;\n"
"    i += 1;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:127
msgid ""
"The pass gives the eight copies counter values `0` through `7`. Constant "
"propagation can then fold expressions derived from those literals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:130
msgid "Partial unrolling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:132
msgid "`#[unroll(4)]` also works when the limit is a runtime value:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:134
msgid ""
"let mut i = 0u32;\n"
"#[unroll(4)]\n"
"while i < n {\n"
"    process(i);\n"
"    i += 1;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:143
msgid ""
"If `n` is `10`, the main loop handles two groups of four iterations. The "
"remainder loop handles iterations `8` and `9`. The result is still correct "
"when `n` is not divisible by four."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:147
msgid ""
"This removes three out of every four main-loop tests and gives the compiler "
"a larger straight-line region to optimize."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:152
msgid "A useful peephole: folding pipeline stages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:154
msgid ""
"Partial unrolling has one wrinkle: the main loop still has a runtime "
"counter. cuda-oxide includes a small **peephole optimization** for a common "
"software-pipeline pattern:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:158
msgid ""
"let mut k_idx = 0u32;\n"
"#[unroll(4)]\n"
"while k_idx < k_iters {\n"
"    let stage = k_idx & 3;\n"
"    match stage {\n"
"        0 => consume_stage_0(),\n"
"        1 => consume_stage_1(),\n"
"        2 => consume_stage_2(),\n"
"        3 => consume_stage_3(),\n"
"        _ => {}\n"
"    }\n"
"    k_idx += 1;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:174
msgid ""
"The unrolled main-loop counter advances by four. Its low two bits therefore "
"do not change between groups, so the four copies have fixed stage values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:177
msgid ""
"copy 0: (k_idx + 0) & 3  →  0\n"
"copy 1: (k_idx + 1) & 3  →  1\n"
"copy 2: (k_idx + 2) & 3  →  2\n"
"copy 3: (k_idx + 3) & 3  →  3\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:184
msgid ""
"The peephole replaces those expressions with literals. Constant propagation "
"then removes the dead `match` arms, leaving four straight-line, stage-"
"specific bodies. The remainder loop stays intact for leftover iterations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:189
msgid ""
"`k_idx % 4` works too when `k_idx` is unsigned, and constant offsets such as "
"`(k_idx + 1) & 3` are also recognized. The pass folds these forms only when "
"their power-of-two period divides the unrolled step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:193
msgid "Why a runtime base does not fold"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:195
msgid "The expression must be based directly on the loop counter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:197
msgid ""
"let stage = k_idx & 3;                    // can fold\n"
"\n"
"let global_k = tile_k_base + k_idx;\n"
"let stage = global_k & 3;                 // tile_k_base is runtime: cannot "
"fold\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:204
msgid ""
"Because the low bits of runtime `tile_k_base` are unknown at compile time, "
"the compiler cannot choose one literal stage for each copy. Rewriting it to "
"the first form is correct only when the algorithm separately guarantees that "
"`tile_k_base` is a multiple of four. The pass deliberately refuses to guess."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:210
msgid ""
"Full unrolling does not need this peephole. A fully unrolled counter is "
"already a literal in every copy, so ordinary constant propagation can do the "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:216
msgid "How the annotation reaches the pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:218
msgid "The source attribute travels through the compiler in six stages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:220
msgid ""
"The `#[kernel]` or `#[device]` macro consumes `#[unroll]` or `#[unroll(N)]` "
"and inserts an internal marker call at the start of that loop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:222
msgid ""
"`mir-importer` recognizes the call and emits a `mir.unroll_hint` operation. "
"The marker produces no runtime code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:224
msgid ""
"`LoopInfo` finds the enclosing loop, while induction analysis finds its "
"counter, start, step, bound, and—when possible—trip count."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:226
msgid ""
"The pass normalizes supported control flow. It joins multiple `continue` "
"paths into one path back to the loop header and routes supported loop-"
"carried values out of a fully unrolled loop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:229
msgid ""
"The transform clones and reconnects the body for full or partial unrolling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:230
msgid ""
"A cleanup phase folds constants, simplifies branches, and removes dead or "
"unreachable code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:233
msgid ""
"The unroll pass leaves functions without an unroll hint untouched. If it "
"cannot prove a requested rewrite is safe, it prints a warning and does not "
"apply the unroll; the loop continues with the same behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:239
msgid "Supported loops and safe fallback"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:241
msgid ""
"The current pass intentionally recognizes a conservative set of loop shapes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/compiler-optimizations.md:243
msgid ""
"Both forms need a counter the pass can follow: a compile-time-constant "
"starting value, the same fixed step on every path back to the header, and a "
"simple, side-effect-free test that directly compares the counter with its "
"bound. The loop must also have one ordinary entry before its header. For "
"unusual or irreducible control flow, the compiler warns and does not unroll "
"the loop."
msgstr ""

